tiores esse. Secundus means to say, if poetry is to be accused, then I know of no more suitable culprit, no more weighty representative of that art than my friend Bassus. So much the more reason for my declining to sit in judgment upon a question in which poetry is involved. -In Aper's ³ Defence of Oratory⁷ which now follows the author has admirably succeeded in individualising the speaker both in style and sentiment. , In his fondness for metaphors, ful- ness of expression, epigrammatic point, conspicuous throughout Α this speech, Aper stands out in bold relief as a true representative of the rhetorical eloquence of his time. That this effect is brought about notwithstanding the fact that the author has repeatedly appropriated Ciceronian ² motives' and phrases proves, on the one hand, that Aper’s defence is not strictly historical, and on the other that Tacitus even in his youth was no servile imitator but an artist who breathed a new originality even into borrowed material.
